Comment: Greetings! Here we have a nice game to learn some important concepts such as develop and how to win having material advantage.

2. .. Qf6? 
Here we have an early queen incursion. Commonly this is a bad move on a very early game.

Good develop of White. Another option could have been 3. Bc4 or even 3. d4
Black aims to f2, but it has no material to support the attack

Notice here that if White have played 4. Nd5! instead of Bc4 Black had to respond 4. .. Qd6 to protect e5 and c7, wining important tempos. 4. Nd5! Qd6 5. Bc4 c6 (or Nf6 6. Nxf6 Qxf6 7. 0-0 0-0 8. d3 and White is ahead) Nc3 Black has several problems to develop Bc8 and Nb8.
As white has no problems, it should play more aggressive in order to punish Qf6. Here d3 allows to play with the black Bishop

Bg5! A very Natural play that it's even better now because of the strength of the two Bishops.

Ng5!? Very interesting move that prevents Bxh3 and threats Bxf7+ wining the queen, but for three pieces (12. .. bxc3 13. Bxf7+ Qxf7 14.  Nxf7 Kxf7  15. bxc3).
Another better way to get advantage is: 12. Na4 Bxh3 13. Bg3 Bg4 14. Nxc5 dxc5 15. Qd2

12. .. Be6? Unnecessary, Rf8 was better.  Now White can capture the Black's white bishop with his knight, keeping the couple of Bishops.
13. Qf3?? Always analyse all the variations. Here the f7 point is defended by three pieces, and attacked now by 2 plus another one by x-rays. So IT'S DEFENDED!, now Black can regain his lost piece.
14. cxb3? Its better to take hxb3 in order to maintain the center and give a column for the "a" Rook.
14. cxb3? Its better to take hxb3 in order to maintain the center and give a column for the "a" Rook.
14. f6?? White couldn't save neither the c3 and g5 Knights. The correct order was: 13. ..Bxb3 14. axb3 bxc3 and White can't save the g5 Knight (Black plays f6 or h6)
15. Ne2?? now the White queen have no scape.. let's see how games continued (Na4 the best option for the Knight)
21. Bxh4?? Black has enough material, don't give them more! Bh2 was the only choise.
